& [WeightingInference_001] is whole_field_weighting_result
  + [inference] is Euler-product and logarithmic-derivative weighting gives a cleaner convergent whole-field surface than sharp or Fejer zero-term truncation for the sampled Re(s) > 1 points
  + [reason] is finite Euler-product and logarithmic-derivative residuals shrink consistently as the prime bound increases across the sampled points
  + [identity_anchor] is -zeta'(s)/zeta(s) is the Dirichlet series over von Mangoldt weights Lambda(n)n^-s, directly tying the surface to prime powers and the same arithmetic fabric behind psi(x)
  + [boundary] is this clean convergence occurs in the half-plane sigma > 1 and should not be read as direct critical-line evidence

& [PrimePowerComparison_001] is boundary_detail
  + [prime_factor_surface] is sum over included primes p <= bound with all repeated powers for those primes through log(p)p^-s/(1-p^-s)
  + [prime_power_cutoff_surface] is sum over finite prime powers p^k <= bound with Lambda(p^k)(p^k)^-s
  + [inference] is both surfaces track the same exact -zeta'(s)/zeta(s) target but expose different truncation boundaries
  + [boundary] is neither truncation should be promoted as theorem authority or as a replacement for explicit-formula zero behavior

& [Conclusion_001] is definite_current_inquiry_conclusion
  + [result] is Euler-product/logarithmic-derivative weighting is the better next whole-field surface for stable prime-power-weighted inspection, but not a better zero-line probe
  + [reason] is the bounded trace shows consistent residual shrinkage in Re(s) > 1 while preserving the convergence boundary away from the critical line
  + [next_relevant_periphery] is approach-to-boundary scans for sigma decreasing toward 1 from above, explicitly marked as convergence-boundary inspection rather than RH evidence
  + [retained_boundary] is special-prime observations remain subordinate to pi(x), theta(x), psi(x), Euler products, explicit-formula error, and zeta-zero behavior

